<div id="Overivew" class="blurbSummary grid_12">
  <div class="p">
    'Web style' deals with the aesthetics and structure of a web site. This
    primer general design principles and guidelines for constructing and
    styling websites.
  </div>
</div><!-- #Overview -->
<div id="Top-Level-Structure" class="blurbSummary grid_12">
  <div class="blurbTitle">Top Level Structure</div>
  <div class="p">
    The first thing to consider is your 'entry points'. The most important
    entry point is the Generally, any page
    may
    be <a href="/documentation/web-style-primer/ref/Lexicon#Deep-Link">directly
    linked (a 'deep link')</a>, but most every site has
    a <a href="/documentation/web-style-primer/ref/Lexicon#Front-Page">front
    page</a> and often one or
    more <a href="/documentation/web-style-primer/ref/Lexicon#Section-Pages">section
    pages</a>.
  </div>
  <div class="p">
    The front page acts as the introduction to the site, and by extension the
    company (or group or individual) that the site is about. It is also a
    reset and jumping off point for general navigation, meaning users will
    often jump to the front page when switching activities or starting a new
    search.
  </div>
  <div class="p">
    The front page should first and foremost be clear and easy to
    navigate, and it is easier to make a good looking web page when we allow
    form to follow function. We discuss particular dos and don'ts in
    the <a href="/documentation/web-style-primer/ref/Front-Page-Design">front
    page design page</a>.
  </div>
</div><!-- #Top-Levels-Structure -->
